      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for NIH at all five operating points using three systematically refined meshes (4.2M, 8.7M, and 17.1M cells).",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation-based GCI was computed following ASME V&V 20. Maximum GCI across operating points was 3.8% (at 2.5 L/min, 2000 RPM). The production mesh (8.7M cells) was selected as the balance between accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid temperature, hematocrit, anticoagulant protocol, rotational speed tolerance) are documented and match simulation boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Bench-top experiments used porcine blood at 37 ± 0.5°C, hematocrit 33 ± 2%, with heparin anticoagulation. Rotational speed was controlled to ± 10 RPM. All conditions are reproduced in CFD boundary conditions within measurement uncertainty bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (validation metric per ASME V&V 20) applied to NIH predictions versus experimental measurements; model is acceptable if the validation metric does not exceed the decision threshold at any operating point.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric was computed at all five operating points. The maximum validation metric value (0.11) is below the acceptance threshold (0.15). Experimental uncertainty was propagated using a Type B evaluation of measurement system specifications."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is directly used in the regulatory submission acceptance criterion (RH < 1) and is consistent with FDA guidance on blood-contacting device evaluation.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the standard regulatory QoI for hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance. The relative hemolysis index RH derived from NIH directly feeds the acceptance decision. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress, exposure time distributions) are also tracked and are mechanistically linked to the power-law hemolysis model used."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments are conducted on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under overlapping operating conditions (flow rates and speeds) as the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation data were generated on the identical FDA generic pump geometry using the same five operating points defined in the COU. Fluid properties and boundary conditions match the COU scenario. The validation domain is judged to be representative of the COU without extrapolation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated by residual drop of at least 4 orders of magnitude and stabilization of NIH monitor point to within 0.1% over the final 500 iterations.",
      "rationale": "All five operating point simulations achieved residual convergence of 5 orders of magnitude. NIH monitor values varied by less than 0.05% over the final 500 iterations, confirming adequate iterative convergence at MRL 2 required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; operator qualification records and simulation setup checklists are maintained as administrative controls.",
      "rationale": "MRL 2 does not require formal use error assessment beyond administrative controls. Simulation setup was performed by a PhD-level CFD engineer with 8 years of cardiovascular CFD experience. A peer review of the simulation setup was conducted by a second engineer prior to production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection (SST k-omega) is justified by literature evidence for rotating blood pump flows; hemolysis power-law model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) is the accepted regulatory standard.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega was selected based on published comparative studies for centrifugal blood pumps showing superior NIH prediction accuracy relative to standard k-epsilon and RSM models. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law is consistent with FDA-accepted practice. Model form uncertainty is acknowledged in the UQ report and bounded by the validation comparison results."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Key model inputs (blood viscosity, inlet velocity profile, rotational speed, hemolysis model coefficients) are characterized with documented sources and uncertainty bounds; Monte Carlo propagation confirms NIH prediction intervals are within acceptable bounds.",
      "rationale": "Input uncertainty characterization was performed for five primary inputs: dynamic viscosity (CV = 6%, log-normal), inlet flow rate (CV = 2%, normal), rotational speed (CV = 0.5%, normal), and hemolysis model coefficients alpha and beta (uniform distributions per Arora et al. 2004). A 5000-sample Monte Carlo propagation was executed. The 95th percentile NIH prediction interval width was 0.0023 mg/dL per 100 L, which is within the decision-relevant uncertainty budget. A screening sensitivity study was also conducted during model development using one-at-a-time (OAT) perturbations of ±10% on each input; results indicated that hemolysis model coefficient alpha and blood viscosity produced the largest NIH responses and are discussed qualitatively in the UQ report. No ranked sensitivity indices were formally computed or archived as a structured analysis record."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; experimental sample documentation (lot numbers, hematocrit measurements, storage conditions) is maintained in the study records.",
      "rationale": "MRL 2 does not require formal test sample characterization beyond standard laboratory documentation. Porcine blood lots used in bench-top validation are documented in the experimental study record with hematocrit, storage time, and anticoagulant details."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; equivalency between validation experiment inputs and COU inputs is addressed qualitatively in the relevance of validation activities assessment.",
      "rationale": "Formal equivalency scoring is not required at MRL 2. The qualitative assessment under 'Relevance of validation activities to the COU' addresses the correspondence between validation and COU input parameters and is judged sufficient for the current model risk level."
